Features:
Ruger® patented chrome-plated, two-stage piston with multi-stage regulator provides a cleaner, cooler running, reliable firearm with superior operating endurance. The two-stage piston provides a smooth power delivery stroke to the bolt carrier.
The four-position chrome-plated gas regulator can be adjusted for optimum reliability and superior operating endurance. The gas system may be closed completely for manual operation during training or when using a suppressor*.
Folding backup iron sights include a windage adjustable rear sight and an elevation adjustable front sight. These sights provide a solid, reliable aiming system that can be folded out of the way to make room for optics, but can be instantly redeployed if needed.

Precision-rifled, chrome-lined, cold hammer-forged Mil-Spec 41V45 chrome-moly-vanadium steel barrel ensures accuracy and longevity.

This is not your typical Integrated Sight Module. This is the version with an IR Laser and Illuminator. Because of this, I will not even consider selling or trading this to you unless you are Active Duty Military or a Law Enforcement Officer. It is not legal to own this unless you are. This unit employs a very powerful laser that is not visible to the human eye and is capable of traveling vast distances, thus giving you the ability to hurt the eyes of others without even knowing it. It is not a "tacti-cool" toy. This is the real deal folks.

This is an older unit and has obviously seen its share of action in the field. I just received it back from Insight where they reviewed its operating status. The IR section is just a hair under their pass marks. The IR co-align is also just .2 mRads out of spec, but should still be good to go. I would rate the glass at 85 percent which is rock bottom. It is probably better than that, but I'm being tough on it considering its age. Included will be the ISM, a wireless remote that can be rail mounted, 2 pressure pads, and an adjustment card as well as a copy of the data sheet from its last evaluation. If you have any questions or would like to see a copy of the spec sheet from Insight, I will be happy to email you a copy. If we reach an agreement, I will need to see proof of service and will make no exceptions to this. 

This is an extremely rare item and finding one is not an easy thing to do. I am asking 1000 cash/trade. If you want trade plus cash scenario we can work something out. I am more than willing to drive to meet anyone. If you are out of state and MIL or LE, I will need to see an email from a .mil or similar email address to confirm you identity. I will only mail it directly to a military or similar mailing address.

Here is a link to the A4 ISM which is the only data I can locate on this module:

http://www.opticsplanet.com/insight-technology-ism-1400-a4-ir-integrated-sighting-module.html

This is me and my boys, Devin and Mason. We live in Washington State.

This week a judge in Winnebago County Wisconsin, Judge Barbara Key, refused to allow Washington to assume jurisdiction. Washington state would be a better authority to determine the best interests of the children because the kids and I have lived in WA for the last 7 years. She disregarded all testimony from my attorney, the Guardian ad litem, and the social worker, who all agreed that WA would be the better authority for further proceedings because it is their home state. Judge Key is not looking out for their best interests and instead is holding a personal vendetta against a man who loves and cares for his kids, a man who has cared for their every need, who has not asked for help from their biological mother in doing so. Judge Key is not looking out for these children's' best interests. She is only interested in removing them from a stable, happy household. She is acting in direct detriment to their safety and well being. 

Call or email Judge Key and ask her to decline jurisdiction. Ask her to allow Washington State to determine their best interests. Ask her to listen to the testimony of the people she appointed to the case.

Judge Barbara Key

 Vickie.belkye@wicourts.gov

Case # 2007FA000847 Roblee v Roblee

Share this plea for help in keeping these boys safe, happy, and healthy right where they are.

I got this rifle a few years back, it has minor pitting on the bolt knob and wood was beat up. I have put around 200 rounds threw it without issue and have used it hunting. Have to many firearms and selling to fund a horse.

What's included:
Rifle, sling
2 double magazine pouches
12 (5 rd) stripper clips loaded with herters steel cased ammo
4 (20 rd) boxes of herters steel cased ammo
1 (55 rd) bandolier of surplus ammo 
1 (25 rd) belt of surplus ammo
10 rounds of Hornady ballistic tipped hunting ammo 
200 (or so) surplus ammo in a ammo box
